D uring the 1975 Tours Colloque,Joel Lefebvre identified Strasbourg‚ Cologne, and Vienna as “centres de gravite” in the development of German humanism.¹ His argument was based on the appearance of a number of defenses of poetry by German humanists, published in those cities between about 1460 and 1520. That series of defenses, according to Lefebvre, culminated in 1518 with the publication of works by several leading humanists: Hermann von dem Busche’s Vallum humanitatis, Johannes Murmellius‘ Scoparius, and Joachim Vadianus' De poetica et carminis ratione. Vadianus’ De poetica has already been treated by Peter Schaffer.² During the last congress of this association‚ I attempted to interpret Busche's Vallum humanitatis.³ I should now like to turn my attention to Murmellius' Scoparius.
